{"id":"1712.04424","submitter":"Bernhard G. Bodmann","authors":"Robert P. Mendez, Bernhard G. Bodmann, Zachery J. Baker, Micah G.\n  Bullock, and Jacob E. McLaney","title":"Binary Parseval frames from group orbits","comments":"26 pages AMSLaTeX, 1 figure","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.RT math.CO math.FA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Binary Parseval frames share many structural properties with real and complex\nones. On the other hand, there are subtle differences, for example that the\nGramian of a binary Parseval frame is characterized as a symmetric idempotent\nwhose range contains at least one odd vector. Here, we study binary Parseval\nframes obtained from the orbit of a vector under a group representation, in\nshort, binary Parseval group frames. In this case, the Gramian of the frame is\nin the algebra generated by the right regular representation. We identify\nequivalence classes of such Parseval frames with binary functions on the group\nthat satisfy a convolution identity. This allows us to find structural\nconstraints for such frames. We use these constraints to catalogue equivalence\nclasses of binary Parseval frames obtained from group representations. As an\napplication, we study the performance of binary Parseval frames generated with\nabelian groups for purposes of error correction. We show that $Z_p^q$ is always\npreferable to $Z_{p^q}$ when searching for best performing codes associated\nwith binary Parseval group frames.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 12 Dec 2017 18:34:37 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-12-13"}
