{"id":"1712.04663","submitter":"Silvan Schmid","authors":"Miao-Hsuan Chien, Mario Brameshuber, Gerhard J. Sch\\\"utz, and Silvan\n  Schmid","title":"Single-molecule optical absorption imaging by nanomechanical\n  photothermal sensing at room temperature","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1073/pnas.1804174115","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.app-ph physics.ins-det","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Absorption microscopy is a powerful technique, enabling the detection of\nsingle non- fluorescent molecules at room temperature. So far, the molecular\nabsorption has been probed optically via the attenuation of a probing laser.\nThe sensitivity of optical probing is not only restricted by background\nscattering, but it is fundamentally limited by laser shot noise. Here, we\npresent nanomechanical photothermal microscopy, which overcomes the scattering\nand shot noise limit by detecting the sample absorption directly with a\ntemperature sensitive substrate. We use nanomechanical silicon nitride drums,\nwhose resonant frequency detunes with local heating. Individual Au\nnanoparticles with diameters from 10 nm - 200 nm and single molecules (Atto\n633) are scanned with a 305 {\\mu}W heating laser with a peak irradiance of 330\n{\\mu}W/{\\mu}m2. Using stress-optimized drums, we achieve a sensitivity of 45\nfW/sqrt(Hz), which results in a signal-to-noise ratio of >60 for a single\nmolecule. Our method has important consequences for a wide range of\napplications, such as imaging, absorption analysis and spectrochemical analysis\nof non-fluorescent samples.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 13 Dec 2017 08:56:21 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-11-21"}
